/* ============================================================
   Reasoning GP — Audio library scripts (1 of 5)
   Cardiovascular · Respiratory · Endocrine.
   Each ~5 min: lay explanation → red flags → risk factors →
   assessment → management (non-drug emphasis) → safety-netting →
   referral. Original summaries based on NICE CKS / NG guidance.
   ============================================================ */
window.RGP_AUDIO_TRACKS = [

  /* ---------------- CARDIOVASCULAR ---------------- */
  { id:'cks-hypertension', cat:'Cardiovascular', ic:'🫀', dur:'5 min', title:'Hypertension', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for hypertension. Definition: persistently raised arterial blood pressure. Stage 1 is a clinic reading of 140 over 90 or higher with an ambulatory or home daytime average of 135 over 85 or higher. Stage 2 is clinic 160 over 100 or higher with a daytime average of 150 over 95 or higher. Severe hypertension is a clinic systolic of 180 or more, or a diastolic of 120 or more. Most cases are primary, with no single identifiable cause. Let us start with the red flags, because they change what you do today. The first is accelerated, or malignant, hypertension — a blood pressure of 180 over 120 or higher together with signs of end-organ damage, such as new retinal haemorrhages or papilloedema on fundoscopy, or symptoms like severe headache, visual disturbance, chest pain, breathlessness, or neurological signs. This needs same-day specialist assessment. The second is suspected phaeochromocytoma — think of it with labile or postural blood pressure, sweating, palpitations, and pallor or headaches in episodes — which also warrants urgent referral. Always exclude a pregnant woman with raised blood pressure, where new hypertension after 20 weeks may signal pre-eclampsia, an obstetric emergency. And in a young person with very high pressure, or hypertension resistant to several drugs, actively consider secondary causes — renal disease, renal artery stenosis, primary hyperaldosteronism or Conn\u2019s, thyroid disease, and the effect of drugs such as steroids, the combined pill, NSAIDs, and recreational stimulants. Now the risk factors, because hypertension rarely travels alone. Non-modifiable factors include increasing age, a family history, and being of Black African or African-Caribbean family origin. The powerful modifiable factors are excess dietary salt, obesity, physical inactivity, excess alcohol, a high-caffeine intake, smoking, poor sleep including untreated sleep apnoea, and stress. These matter both because they raise the pressure and because tackling them is genuine treatment. Now, how to explain the diagnosis in plain language to the patient. I would say something like this: blood pressure is the force of blood pushing against the walls of your arteries. When it stays too high over months and years, it makes the heart work harder and slowly damages the blood vessels, which raises the risk of a stroke, a heart attack, kidney damage, and problems with sight. It usually causes no symptoms at all, which is exactly why it is worth treating — we are not chasing how you feel today, we are protecting your future health. The good news is that it responds very well to changes you can make, and to simple, well-tested tablets if needed. Assessment: never diagnose on a single reading. Confirm with ambulatory monitoring, or home readings if that is not tolerated, and measure in both arms at the first visit, using the higher-reading arm thereafter. Assess for end-organ damage and overall cardiovascular risk — check urine for protein and blood, bloods for renal function, HbA1c and lipids, do an ECG, examine the fundi, and calculate a QRISK score. Now management, and I want to dwell on the non-drug measures, because they are first-line and often underplayed. Advise a diet low in salt — aiming below six grams a day — and rich in fruit, vegetables and wholegrains, the DASH pattern. Encourage regular physical activity, weight loss if overweight, reducing alcohol to within recommended limits, cutting caffeine if intake is high, stopping smoking, and improving sleep. These can lower systolic pressure by clinically meaningful amounts and may avoid medication altogether in stage 1. Offer drug treatment to anyone with stage 2, and to those under 80 with stage 1 who also have end-organ damage, established cardiovascular disease, renal disease, diabetes, or a ten-year risk of 10 percent or more. The step-care pathway: for people under 55 not of Black African or Caribbean origin, start an ACE inhibitor or an angiotensin-receptor blocker. For those 55 or over, or of Black African or Caribbean family origin of any age, start a calcium-channel blocker. Step 2 combines the two; step 3 adds a thiazide-like diuretic; and step 4, for resistant hypertension, adds low-dose spironolactone if the potassium is below 4.5, or an alpha- or beta-blocker. Aim for a clinic target below 140 over 90 under 80, and below 150 over 90 at 80 or over, with lower home targets. Now safety-netting, which matters enormously here. Tell the patient to seek urgent help — and think of malignant hypertension or another emergency — if they develop a sudden severe headache, chest pain, breathlessness, visual loss, weakness or speech disturbance, or in pregnancy. Warn about postural dizziness when starting drugs, and check renal function and electrolytes one to two weeks after starting or changing an ACE inhibitor, ARB, or diuretic. Refer urgently for same-day assessment if there is accelerated hypertension or suspected phaeochromocytoma, and consider specialist referral for suspected secondary causes, resistant hypertension, or hypertension in the young. Review at least annually once stable, reinforcing lifestyle at every contact, and remember the central message: treating a number that causes no symptoms is one of the most effective things we do to prevent stroke and heart disease.' },

  { id:'cks-heart-failure', cat:'Cardiovascular', ic:'🫀', dur:'5 min', title:'Chronic heart failure', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for chronic heart failure. In plain language for the patient: heart failure does not mean the heart is about to stop — it means the heart muscle has become too weak or too stiff to pump blood as efficiently as it should, so fluid can back up into the lungs and legs, leaving you breathless and tired. It is a long-term condition, but with the right treatment most people feel substantially better and live longer. Definition: a syndrome of breathlessness, fatigue and fluid retention from structural or functional cardiac impairment, classified by ejection fraction into reduced or preserved. Let us start with the red flags, because they change what you do today. Acute decompensation — severe breathlessness at rest, unable to lie flat, frothy or pink sputum, low oxygen saturations, or signs of poor perfusion — is a medical emergency needing 999 and admission. Be alert to a very high or very low heart rate, syncope, or chest pain suggesting acute coronary syndrome, and to a weight gain of more than two kilograms over a few days, which signals fluid retention. Now the risk factors, which are also the common causes: a previous heart attack and coronary disease, long-standing high blood pressure, valve disease, atrial fibrillation, diabetes, obesity, excess alcohol, and some chemotherapy drugs. Assessment: suspect heart failure from breathlessness, ankle swelling, fatigue, orthopnoea, and waking breathless at night, with a raised JVP, a displaced apex, a third heart sound, and basal crackles. Measure NT-proBNP: above 2000 nanograms per litre, refer urgently for specialist assessment and echocardiography within two weeks; between 400 and 2000, refer within six weeks. Also do an ECG, bloods, and chest X-ray. Now management, and the non-drug foundations matter as much as the tablets. Advise daily weights at the same time each morning, with a written action plan to seek help if weight rises by more than around two kilograms over a few days. Restrict excess salt and avoid very high fluid intakes; moderate alcohol and stop smoking; stay as active as possible, and refer to a cardiac rehabilitation or supervised exercise programme, which improves symptoms and quality of life. Ensure the annual flu jab and a one-off pneumococcal vaccination. For heart failure with reduced ejection fraction, the disease-modifying drugs that improve survival are introduced and titrated together where possible — an ACE inhibitor or ARB, or sacubitril-valsartan; a beta-blocker licensed for heart failure; a mineralocorticoid receptor antagonist such as spironolactone or eplerenone; and an SGLT2 inhibitor such as dapagliflozin. Use a loop diuretic such as furosemide to relieve congestion, titrated to symptoms, but it controls fluid rather than prolonging life. Monitor renal function and potassium after starting or up-titrating these drugs. Now safety-netting: tell the patient to seek urgent help for worsening breathlessness, breathlessness at rest or lying flat, rapid weight gain or increasing swelling, chest pain, blackouts, or palpitations, and to weigh themselves daily and act on their plan. Review medication adherence and avoid drugs that worsen heart failure, such as NSAIDs. Refer for specialist confirmation and titration, for consideration of device therapy in selected patients, and to community heart-failure or palliative teams as the condition progresses. Review regularly, optimising the four pillars to the maximum tolerated doses, and revisit the plain-language message: the tablets are not just to ease symptoms but to protect the heart and prolong life, so it is worth persevering with them.' },

  { id:'cks-af', cat:'Cardiovascular', ic:'💓', dur:'5 min', title:'Atrial fibrillation', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for atrial fibrillation. In plain language for the patient: atrial fibrillation is an irregular, often fast heart rhythm caused by chaotic electrical activity in the top chambers of the heart. It matters for two reasons — it can make you feel palpitations, breathless or tired, and, more importantly, the irregular flow lets blood pool and form clots, which can travel to the brain and cause a stroke. The good news is that a daily blood-thinning tablet dramatically reduces that stroke risk. Definition: a supraventricular tachyarrhythmia with uncoordinated atrial activity and an irregularly irregular ventricular response, classed as paroxysmal, persistent, or permanent. Red flags first, because they change what you do today: AF with chest pain, severe breathlessness, syncope, or signs of haemodynamic instability — a very fast rate with low blood pressure — is an emergency needing 999 and may require urgent cardioversion. New AF with focal neurological signs raises concern for a stroke and needs emergency assessment. Now the risk factors: increasing age, high blood pressure, heart failure, valve and coronary disease, diabetes, obesity, obstructive sleep apnoea, excess alcohol, and an overactive thyroid. Assessment: suspect AF from palpitations, breathlessness, or an irregular pulse; confirm with a 12-lead ECG, using ambulatory monitoring for paroxysmal cases. Look for underlying causes such as hypertension, valve and thyroid disease and alcohol, examine for heart failure, and check bloods including thyroid function, renal function, and a full blood count. Management has two parallel aims — preventing stroke, and controlling symptoms. For stroke prevention, calculate the CHA2DS2-VASc score; offer anticoagulation if it is 2 or more, and consider it in men with a score of 1. A direct oral anticoagulant such as apixaban or edoxaban is first-line, ahead of warfarin. Assess bleeding risk with ORBIT, addressing modifiable factors — blood pressure, alcohol, and risky medicines — rather than withholding anticoagulation. Do not offer aspirin solely for stroke prevention in AF. Now the non-drug and lifestyle measures, which are genuine treatment: reducing alcohol, losing weight, treating sleep apnoea, controlling blood pressure and diabetes, and staying active all reduce the burden of AF and help keep the rhythm stable. For rate control, offer a standard beta-blocker, not sotalol, or a rate-limiting calcium-channel blocker such as diltiazem, as first-line monotherapy; digoxin is reserved for sedentary people. Consider a rhythm-control strategy — with referral — where symptoms persist despite rate control, the AF is of recent onset, or there is a reversible cause or heart failure. Now safety-netting: explain the symptoms of stroke using the FAST message — facial droop, arm weakness, speech difficulty, time to call 999 — and tell the patient to seek urgent help for chest pain, blackouts, or severe breathlessness. Counsel anyone on anticoagulation about bleeding — to seek help for significant or unusual bleeding, black stools, or a head injury — and not to stop the drug without advice. Refer urgently or admit for haemodynamic instability or suspected stroke, and refer to cardiology for rhythm-control assessment, for paroxysmal AF needing intervention, or where the diagnosis or management is uncertain. Review the rate, symptoms, and stroke and bleeding risk regularly, reinforcing the central point that the anticoagulant is the part of treatment that prevents the most serious harm.' },

  { id:'cks-angina', cat:'Cardiovascular', ic:'🫀', dur:'5 min', title:'Stable angina', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for stable angina. In plain language for the patient: angina is a tight, heavy or gripping discomfort in the chest that comes on with exertion or stress and eases with rest. It happens because the arteries supplying the heart muscle have narrowed, so during exertion the muscle cannot get all the blood it needs. It is a warning sign of furred-up heart arteries, and although it can be frightening, stable angina is very treatable — with tablets to relieve and prevent the pain, treatments to lower the risk of a heart attack, and sometimes a procedure to open the arteries. Definition: chest pain from myocardial ischaemia, classically provoked by exertion or emotion and relieved within minutes by rest or nitrates, caused by coronary artery disease. Red flags first: pain that becomes more frequent, comes on at rest or with minimal exertion, lasts longer, or is rapidly worsening suggests unstable angina or an acute coronary syndrome — this is an emergency needing 999, not a routine referral. Pain with breathlessness, sweating, nausea, or collapse likewise needs emergency assessment. Now the risk factors, which are the targets of treatment: smoking, high blood pressure, high cholesterol, diabetes, obesity, physical inactivity, a poor diet, increasing age, male sex, and a family history of premature coronary disease. Assessment: characterise the pain against the three typical features — constricting discomfort in the chest, neck, jaw or arm; precipitated by exertion; and relieved by rest or GTN within about five minutes. Three features suggest typical angina, two atypical. Examine for anaemia, valve disease, and risk factors, do an ECG, and check bloods including full blood count, HbA1c, lipids, renal and thyroid function. NICE recommends CT coronary angiography as the first-line investigation for suspected stable angina. Management: for rapid symptom relief, give a short-acting nitrate, GTN spray, for acute episodes and to use before predictable exertion, and teach its use — sit down, repeat after five minutes, and call 999 if pain persists beyond the second dose. For preventing attacks, offer first-line either a beta-blocker or a calcium-channel blocker, switching or combining if symptoms persist; if these are not tolerated, consider a long-acting nitrate, ivabradine, nicorandil, or ranolazine. Crucially, the non-drug and secondary-prevention measures do the long-term work: support smoking cessation, a Mediterranean-style diet, regular physical activity within symptom limits, weight loss, and good control of blood pressure and diabetes; refer to cardiac rehabilitation or structured exercise. For prevention of heart attack and death, offer a statin and an antiplatelet such as aspirin, and an ACE inhibitor if there is diabetes or other indication. Now safety-netting: make sure the patient knows the difference between their usual, predictable angina and an emergency — pain at rest, lasting more than ten minutes, or not settling after GTN means call 999. Discuss when angina affects driving, and that they must not drive during unstable symptoms. Refer to cardiology to confirm the diagnosis and to assess for revascularisation when symptoms are not controlled on optimal treatment, and refer urgently or admit for unstable symptoms. Review regularly, optimising symptom control and, above all, the secondary-prevention treatments and risk factors that prevent future events.' },

  { id:'cks-lipids', cat:'Cardiovascular', ic:'🩸', dur:'5 min', title:'Lipid modification & CVD prevention', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for lipid modification and cardiovascular disease prevention. In plain language for the patient: cholesterol is a fatty substance in the blood. Too much of the harmful type slowly builds up in the artery walls, narrowing them and raising the risk of heart attacks and strokes. Lowering it — with healthy changes and, where the risk is high enough, a statin — reduces that risk, and statins are among the most studied and safest preventive medicines we have. The aim is to reduce cardiovascular risk through lifestyle and, where indicated, lipid-lowering therapy. Red flags and special situations first: very high cholesterol — a total above 7.5, or above 9 — or a strong family history of early heart disease should prompt you to think of familial hypercholesterolaemia, which needs specialist assessment and family testing. Very high triglycerides, above about 10, raise the risk of pancreatitis and need urgent attention. And remember that anyone with established cardiovascular disease is already high-risk and does not need a risk score. Now the risk factors that drive cardiovascular risk: smoking, high blood pressure, diabetes, obesity, physical inactivity, an unhealthy diet, excess alcohol, increasing age, male sex, family history, and certain ethnic backgrounds, alongside the lipid profile itself. Assessment: for primary prevention, calculate the ten-year cardiovascular risk using QRISK3 in people up to 84 without established disease, diabetes, or familial hypercholesterolaemia. Before starting treatment, measure a full lipid profile, HbA1c, renal, liver and thyroid function, and consider secondary causes of dyslipidaemia. Management, beginning with the non-drug foundation that applies to everyone: a cardioprotective diet — replacing saturated with unsaturated fats, more fruit, vegetables, wholegrains and oily fish — regular physical activity, achieving a healthy weight, limiting alcohol, and stopping smoking. These reduce risk regardless of whether a statin is started. For primary prevention, offer atorvastatin 20 milligrams if the ten-year QRISK is 10 percent or more, after an informed discussion about benefit and the small risks; offer it also to most people with chronic kidney disease and to those with type 1 diabetes with risk factors. For secondary prevention, in established cardiovascular disease, offer high-intensity atorvastatin 80 milligrams unless contraindicated. Check liver function before and within a few months, and a lipid response at two to three months, aiming for a greater than 40 percent reduction in non-HDL cholesterol. If the response is inadequate despite adherence on the maximum tolerated statin, add ezetimibe, and follow local pathways for injectable agents such as PCSK9 inhibitors or inclisiran. Manage statin intolerance by confirming it is genuine, rechecking after a break, and trying a lower dose or alternative statin before abandoning treatment. Now safety-netting: warn about unexplained, severe or widespread muscle pain, particularly with dark urine, which rarely indicates myositis and warrants stopping the statin and checking creatine kinase. Reassure about the common myths, and emphasise that benefit comes from sustained treatment over years. Refer for suspected familial hypercholesterolaemia, very high triglycerides, or failure to reach targets on combination therapy. Review adherence, lifestyle, and the lipid profile, reinforcing that consistent risk-factor control over time is what prevents heart attacks and strokes.' },

  { id:'cks-dvt', cat:'Cardiovascular', ic:'🦵', dur:'5 min', title:'Deep vein thrombosis', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for deep vein thrombosis. In plain language for the patient: a DVT is a blood clot that forms in one of the deep veins, usually in the leg. It causes a swollen, painful, sometimes warm and red calf or thigh. It matters because part of the clot can break off and travel to the lungs — a pulmonary embolism — which can be life-threatening, so we treat it promptly with blood-thinning medicine. Definition: a thrombus in a deep vein, usually of the leg, which can embolise to the lungs. Red flags first, and they are critical: symptoms of pulmonary embolism — sudden breathlessness, chest pain worse on breathing, coughing blood, dizziness or collapse — are a medical emergency needing 999. A painful, swollen, blue or white leg with compromised circulation is a limb emergency. Now the risk factors, which both raise suspicion and guide how long to treat: recent surgery or immobility, long-haul travel, active cancer, pregnancy and the postpartum period, the combined pill or HRT, obesity, increasing age, a previous clot, and inherited thrombophilias. Assessment: suspect DVT with unilateral leg pain, swelling, warmth, and tenderness, and measure and compare calf circumference. Use the two-level DVT Wells score to estimate probability. If DVT is likely, with a Wells score of 2 or more, arrange a proximal leg vein ultrasound within four hours, or, if not available, give interim anticoagulation and a D-dimer with a scan within 24 hours. If DVT is unlikely, a score of 1 or less, do a D-dimer; if positive, proceed to ultrasound. Examine for signs of pulmonary embolism, and in unprovoked cases consider an underlying cause including occult malignancy. Management: offer anticoagulation once DVT is confirmed, or interim treatment while awaiting a scan. First-line is a direct oral anticoagulant such as apixaban or rivaroxaban. Continue for at least three months; for a provoked DVT with a transient cause, stop at three months, while unprovoked DVT, ongoing risk factors, or active cancer warrant longer or indefinite anticoagulation after weighing bleeding risk. Now the non-drug and supportive measures: encourage mobilisation and leg elevation, advise that early walking is safe and helpful, and consider compression stockings only for persistent post-thrombotic symptoms rather than routinely. Address modifiable risk — weight, stopping the combined pill where relevant, and movement on long journeys. Now safety-netting, which is vital: tell every patient the symptoms of pulmonary embolism and to call 999 if they develop sudden breathlessness, chest pain on breathing, or cough up blood. Counsel on anticoagulant bleeding risk, to seek help for significant bleeding, and not to stop the drug without advice. Refer or admit those with suspected pulmonary embolism, severe symptoms, a limb-threatening clot, or where outpatient management is unsuitable — for example significant bleeding risk, severe renal impairment, or pregnancy, which needs low-molecular-weight heparin and specialist care. Investigate for cancer based on clinical assessment in unprovoked cases. Review at three months to decide on the duration of treatment, and arrange follow-up for the anticoagulation plan and any underlying cause.' },

  { id:'cks-pad', cat:'Cardiovascular', ic:'🦵', dur:'5 min', title:'Peripheral arterial disease', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for peripheral arterial disease. In plain language for the patient: this is furring and narrowing of the arteries that carry blood to the legs, the same process that affects the heart arteries. The classic symptom is a cramping pain in the calf when you walk that eases when you stop. It is important for two reasons — it can limit walking and, in severe cases, threaten the limb, and it is a strong signal that the arteries elsewhere, including to the heart and brain, are also affected, so it is really a whole-body warning to protect against heart attacks and strokes. Definition: atherosclerotic narrowing of the arteries supplying the limbs, ranging from intermittent claudication to critical limb ischaemia. Red flags first: critical limb ischaemia — rest pain, especially at night and relieved by hanging the leg down, ulceration, or gangrene — is a limb-threatening emergency. Acute limb ischaemia — a sudden painful, pale, pulseless, perishingly cold, paraesthetic and paralysed leg — needs emergency vascular admission within hours. Now the risk factors, which are also the treatment targets: smoking, which is the strongest, plus diabetes, high blood pressure, high cholesterol, increasing age, and a family history of vascular disease. Assessment: suspect it from cramping calf, thigh or buttock pain on walking that is relieved by rest, and from cold, pale legs, hair loss, and slow-healing wounds. Examine the peripheral pulses, look for ulcers and gangrene, and measure the ankle-brachial pressure index — below 0.9 supports the diagnosis, while a falsely high value above 1.4 may occur with calcified vessels in diabetes. Check bloods including HbA1c and lipids and assess overall cardiovascular risk. Management: because peripheral arterial disease is a marker of widespread atherosclerosis, the priority is aggressive secondary prevention — and the single most effective measure is stopping smoking, which I would emphasise above all else. Add a statin, an antiplatelet such as clopidogrel, and optimise blood pressure and diabetes. For intermittent claudication, the cornerstone treatment is a supervised exercise programme — walking to near-maximal pain, repeatedly — which genuinely improves walking distance and is recommended before considering procedures. Give meticulous foot-care advice, especially in diabetes — well-fitting footwear, daily inspection, prompt attention to any wound. Now safety-netting: tell the patient to seek urgent help for a sudden cold, painful, pale leg, for rest pain, or for any non-healing wound, ulcer or area of blackened skin on the foot, as these signal a threatened limb. Refer to vascular services for consideration of angioplasty or bypass if exercise and risk-factor management do not control symptoms, urgently for critical limb ischaemia, and as an emergency for acute limb ischaemia. Review cardiovascular risk and symptoms regularly, reinforcing at every visit that smoking cessation and exercise are the most powerful treatments, both for the legs and for preventing heart attacks and strokes.' },

  { id:'cks-palpitations', cat:'Cardiovascular', ic:'💗', dur:'5 min', title:'Palpitations', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for palpitations. In plain language for the patient: palpitations are an awareness of your own heartbeat — it may feel fast, thumping, fluttering, skipping or pounding. Most palpitations are harmless, often just the heart beating a little forcefully or the odd extra beat, frequently brought on by caffeine, stress, alcohol or tiredness. Sometimes, though, they are due to an abnormal heart rhythm, and a small number point to something that needs treatment, so it is worth checking. Definition: an awareness of the heartbeat, with causes ranging from benign ectopics and sinus tachycardia to arrhythmias, and non-cardiac causes such as anxiety, an overactive thyroid, anaemia, fever, and stimulants. Red flags first, because they decide urgency: palpitations with syncope or near-blackout, with chest pain or severe breathlessness, occurring during exertion, or in someone with a family history of sudden cardiac death or known heart disease, all raise concern for a dangerous arrhythmia and warrant urgent assessment. Now the risk factors and contributors: structural or ischaemic heart disease, heart failure, thyroid disease, anaemia, electrolyte disturbance, anxiety, excess caffeine and alcohol, stimulant and recreational drugs, and some prescribed medicines. Assessment: take a careful history of the rhythm — ask the patient to tap it out — and of the onset and offset, the triggers, and associated symptoms. Examine the pulse and heart, and look for signs of thyroid disease or anaemia, and check the blood pressure. Investigate with a 12-lead ECG, looking for arrhythmia, pre-excitation as in Wolff-Parkinson-White, a prolonged QT interval, or evidence of structural disease, and check bloods including full blood count, thyroid function, and electrolytes. For intermittent symptoms with a normal resting ECG, arrange ambulatory monitoring matched to how often symptoms occur — a 24-hour or longer Holter for frequent episodes, or an event or patch recorder for infrequent ones. Management: where the cause is benign, such as ectopic beats or sinus tachycardia, the most powerful intervention is explanation and reassurance, alongside reducing caffeine, alcohol, stimulants, and addressing stress and sleep. Treat any identified cause — thyroid disease, anaemia, anxiety — and manage confirmed arrhythmias according to type, such as atrial fibrillation or supraventricular tachycardia. Now safety-netting, which should be explicit: advise the patient to call 999 if palpitations are accompanied by blackout, chest pain, or severe breathlessness, and to seek prompt review if they become more frequent, more sustained, or change in character. Teach simple vagal manoeuvres where appropriate for known supraventricular tachycardia. Refer urgently or admit those with palpitations and syncope, an abnormal ECG suggesting a serious arrhythmia, or a family history of sudden death; refer to cardiology for sustained or symptomatic arrhythmias, suspected structural heart disease, or where the diagnosis remains unclear despite monitoring. The reassuring close for most patients is that, once a dangerous rhythm has been excluded, palpitations are common and benign and settle with simple measures.' },

  { id:'cks-acs-secondary', cat:'Cardiovascular', ic:'❤️', dur:'5 min', title:'Post-MI secondary prevention', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for secondary prevention after a myocardial infarction. In plain language for the patient: after a heart attack, the goal is to protect the heart and prevent another one. That means a small group of tablets taken long-term, a structured rehabilitation programme, and changes to the things that caused the problem in the first place. Taken together, these dramatically lower the chance of a further heart attack and help you live longer and feel better. The aim is to reduce the risk of further cardiovascular events and death, and primary care plays a central role after discharge. Red flags first: recurrent chest pain, especially at rest or worsening, breathlessness suggesting heart failure, blackouts, or palpitations after discharge all warrant prompt or emergency reassessment, as they may signal re-infarction, heart failure, or arrhythmia. Now the risk factors to address — the same ones that caused the event: smoking, high cholesterol, high blood pressure, diabetes, obesity, inactivity, and a poor diet, alongside low mood, which is common after a heart attack and worsens outcomes. Assessment: review the patient after discharge, confirm the diagnosis and any procedures performed, reconcile medications, and assess symptoms, left ventricular function, cardiovascular risk factors, mood, and readiness for cardiac rehabilitation. Check renal function and lipids. Management centres on the secondary-prevention medicines that everyone should be considered for. Offer dual antiplatelet therapy — aspirin plus a second agent such as ticagrelor or clopidogrel — usually for up to twelve months, then aspirin indefinitely. Offer a high-intensity statin, atorvastatin 80 milligrams, aiming for a substantial reduction in non-HDL cholesterol. Offer an ACE inhibitor, titrated to the maximum tolerated dose, and a beta-blocker, continued for at least twelve months and indefinitely if there is left ventricular dysfunction. Add a mineralocorticoid receptor antagonist if there is heart failure with reduced ejection fraction. Now the non-drug measures, which are just as important: refer every suitable patient to cardiac rehabilitation, which improves survival and confidence, and give comprehensive lifestyle advice — stopping smoking, a Mediterranean-style diet, gradually increasing physical activity, weight management, and limiting alcohol. Actively ask about mood and treat depression and anxiety. Discuss the practical questions patients worry about — when they can return to work, the driving rules after a heart attack, and resuming sexual activity, reassuring that this is generally safe once they can manage moderate exertion. Now safety-netting: ensure the patient knows to call 999 for chest pain that is severe, lasts more than fifteen minutes, or does not settle with their GTN, and to seek help for increasing breathlessness, ankle swelling, or blackouts. Stress that the preventive tablets should not be stopped without advice. Refer back to cardiology for recurrent symptoms, heart failure, or arrhythmia. Review medication adherence, blood pressure, lipids, glucose, and lifestyle regularly, reinforcing that sustained adherence to this combination is what most reduces the risk of another event.' },

  /* ---------------- RESPIRATORY ---------------- */
  { id:'cks-asthma', cat:'Respiratory', ic:'🌬️', dur:'5 min', title:'Asthma', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for asthma in adults and adolescents. In plain language for the patient: asthma is a condition where the airways in the lungs are sensitive and become inflamed and narrowed, causing wheeze, cough, chest tightness and breathlessness, often in episodes. The key idea to get across is that there are two kinds of treatment — a reliever that opens the airways quickly, and a preventer, an inhaled steroid, that calms the underlying inflammation. The modern approach is that everyone needs the preventer, because relying on the reliever alone leaves the inflammation untreated and is actually a marker of risk. Definition: a chronic inflammatory airway condition with variable, reversible airflow obstruction. Red flags first, because acute asthma kills: features of a life-threatening attack — a silent chest, exhaustion, confusion, cyanosis, a falling heart rate, or oxygen saturations below 92 percent — need 999 and immediate treatment. Markers of an at-risk patient include previous near-fatal asthma, frequent reliever use, repeated attacks, and poor adherence. Now the risk factors and triggers: a personal or family history of atopy — eczema and hay fever — exposure to allergens such as house dust mite, pollen and pets, viral infections, cold air, exercise, smoking and air pollution, and occupational exposures. Assessment: suspect asthma from wheeze, breathlessness, chest tightness and cough that are variable, worse at night or early morning, and triggered by the factors just mentioned. Diagnosis now uses objective testing — the fractional exhaled nitric oxide, FeNO, and spirometry with bronchodilator reversibility, with peak-flow variability if needed, following the 2024 joint NICE, BTS and SIGN guideline. Management reflects that updated guidance, and the central principle is that no one should be treated with a short-acting reliever alone. First-line is a combination low-dose inhaled corticosteroid plus formoterol inhaler used only as needed — the anti-inflammatory reliever, or AIR, approach. If symptoms are uncontrolled or treatment is needed regularly, move to maintenance and reliever therapy, MART, where the same combination inhaler is taken daily and as the reliever. Step up the inhaled corticosteroid dose within MART if control remains poor. Crucially, before ever escalating, always check the basics — inhaler technique, adherence, and trigger exposure — as these explain most poor control. Now the non-drug essentials: every patient needs a written personalised asthma action plan telling them how to recognise worsening asthma and what to do; address smoking, including passive smoke; review trigger avoidance; ensure the annual flu vaccine; and arrange at least an annual review, plus a review after any attack. Now safety-netting, which is central: teach patients to recognise an attack — needing the reliever more often, waking at night, or struggling to do usual activities — to start their action plan, and to call 999 if the reliever is not helping, they cannot speak in full sentences, or they are exhausted. Manage acute attacks by severity with salbutamol, oral prednisolone, and admission for severe or life-threatening features, with follow-up within 48 hours. Refer for diagnostic uncertainty, poor control despite good adherence and technique, suspected occupational asthma, or any life-threatening attack, and to specialist severe-asthma services for those needing high-dose or biologic therapy.' },

  { id:'cks-copd', cat:'Respiratory', ic:'🫁', dur:'5 min', title:'COPD', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, following NICE guideline NG115. In plain language for the patient: COPD is long-term damage to the lungs and airways, usually caused by smoking, which makes them narrowed and the air sacs less elastic, so you become breathless, cough, and bring up phlegm. The damage already done cannot be reversed, but a great deal can be done to ease symptoms, prevent flare-ups, and stop it getting worse — and stopping smoking is the single most powerful thing, because it is the one intervention that actually slows the decline. Definition: a progressive disorder with persistent respiratory symptoms and airflow obstruction that is not fully reversible. Red flags first: an exacerbation with marked breathlessness, confusion or drowsiness, cyanosis, or low oxygen saturations needs emergency assessment; consider also pneumonia, heart failure, a pneumothorax, or a pulmonary embolism when someone deteriorates. Weight loss and haemoptysis should prompt thinking about lung cancer. Now the risk factors: smoking above all, plus occupational dusts and fumes, air pollution, and the rare alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency, which is worth considering in younger patients or never-smokers. Assessment: suspect COPD in a person over 35 with a risk factor who has exertional breathlessness, chronic cough, regular sputum, or frequent winter chest infections. Confirm with post-bronchodilator spirometry showing an FEV1 to FVC ratio below 0.7. Assess severity by FEV1, the symptom burden using the MRC dyspnoea scale, and exacerbation frequency, and do a chest X-ray to exclude other disease, a full blood count for anaemia or polycythaemia, and a BMI. Management foundations, which I want to stress are mostly non-drug: support smoking cessation at every opportunity with behavioural support and pharmacotherapy; offer pulmonary rehabilitation to anyone limited by breathlessness, as it improves exercise capacity and quality of life as much as any inhaler; give the annual influenza and one-off pneumococcal vaccines; and encourage physical activity and good nutrition. For inhaled therapy, start a short-acting bronchodilator as needed, then offer a combination long-acting bronchodilator — a LABA plus a LAMA — for persistent breathlessness. Add an inhaled corticosteroid, making triple therapy, where there are asthmatic features or steroid responsiveness, or continued exacerbations despite dual therapy, considering the blood eosinophil count. Provide a self-management plan and, for suitable patients, a rescue pack of steroids and antibiotics to start during exacerbations. Now safety-netting: teach patients to recognise an exacerbation — more breathlessness, more sputum, or a change in its colour — to start their rescue pack if they have one, and to seek urgent help for severe breathlessness, drowsiness, confusion, or blue lips. Treat exacerbations with bronchodilators, oral prednisolone, and antibiotics if the sputum is purulent. Refer for specialist assessment with diagnostic doubt, severe or rapidly progressive disease, suspected cor pulmonale, or assessment for long-term oxygen therapy — which is for chronic low oxygen levels and must never be given as symptomatic relief to a continuing smoker because of the fire risk and lack of benefit. Review at least annually, checking inhaler technique, smoking status, and exacerbations, and revisit the central message that stopping smoking changes the course of the disease.' },

  { id:'cks-pneumonia', cat:'Respiratory', ic:'🫁', dur:'5 min', title:'Community-acquired pneumonia', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for community-acquired pneumonia in adults. In plain language for the patient: pneumonia is an infection of the lung tissue itself, not just the airways, which fills part of the lung with inflammation and fluid. That is why it causes a cough, fever, and breathlessness and can make you quite unwell. Most people treated at home recover well with antibiotics and time, but it is important to know the signs that mean you need to be seen urgently. Definition: an acute lower respiratory tract infection with new chest signs and systemic features. Red flags first, because severity assessment guides everything: confusion, a high respiratory rate, low blood pressure, low oxygen saturations, or signs of sepsis indicate severe illness needing emergency admission. Be especially careful in older, frail, or immunosuppressed patients, in whom signs can be subtle. Now the risk factors: increasing age, smoking, COPD and other chronic lung disease, heart, liver, kidney or neurological disease, diabetes, immunosuppression, and recent viral infection. Assessment: suspect pneumonia with cough, fever, breathlessness, pleuritic chest pain, and sputum, with focal chest signs such as crackles, bronchial breathing, or dullness to percussion. In the community, assess severity with the CRB-65 score — one point each for new Confusion, a Respiratory rate of 30 or more, low Blood pressure with systolic under 90 or diastolic 60 or below, and age 65 or over. A score of 0 suggests low risk suitable for home treatment; 1 to 2 raises risk and prompts considering hospital; 3 or more is high risk needing urgent admission. Use clinical judgement alongside the score, and check oxygen saturations and observations. A chest X-ray confirms the diagnosis but is not always needed for mild community cases. Management: for low-severity pneumonia managed at home, offer first-line amoxicillin for five days, with a macrolide or doxycycline if penicillin-allergic, following local guidance, plus advice on fluids, rest, and antipyretics. Now the non-drug and supportive care: encourage plenty of fluids and rest, simple analgesia for pleuritic pain and fever, and not smoking. Now safety-netting, which is essential because pneumonia can deteriorate: tell the patient and family to seek urgent help — and call 999 if severe — for worsening breathlessness, confusion, a high fever that does not settle, inability to keep fluids down, or failure to improve after about three days of antibiotics. Advise that recovery is gradual, with tiredness and cough lasting weeks. Arrange a follow-up chest X-ray at around six weeks for those with persisting symptoms or at higher risk of underlying malignancy — for example smokers over 50 — because pneumonia can be the first presentation of lung cancer. Refer or admit those with a high CRB-65 score, low saturations, sepsis, significant comorbidity, or social circumstances that make home care unsafe. Reinforce smoking cessation and ensure influenza and pneumococcal vaccination after recovery.' },

  { id:'cks-rhinitis', cat:'Respiratory', ic:'🤧', dur:'5 min', title:'Allergic rhinitis', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for allergic rhinitis. In plain language for the patient: allergic rhinitis is when the lining of the nose reacts to something you are allergic to — most often pollen, house dust mite, or animal dander — causing sneezing, an itchy, runny or blocked nose, and often itchy, watery eyes. It is not dangerous, but it can be genuinely miserable and disrupt sleep, concentration and work, and it often goes hand in hand with asthma. The reassuring message is that it can usually be controlled well with the right treatment used correctly and consistently. Definition: IgE-mediated inflammation of the nasal mucosa from allergen exposure, classified as seasonal, perennial, or occupational, and by severity. Red flags and things not to miss first: unilateral symptoms, a bloody or one-sided discharge, persistent crusting, facial pain, or a visible mass should prompt thinking about other diagnoses including, rarely, sinonasal tumours, and warrant examination and referral. Nasal polyps cause persistent blockage and loss of smell and need assessment. Now the risk factors: a personal or family history of atopy, exposure to the relevant allergens, and occupational sensitisers. Assessment: diagnose clinically from sneezing, nasal itch, watery rhinorrhoea, and congestion, often with itchy watery eyes, in a seasonal or perennial pattern with identifiable triggers. Ask specifically about the impact on sleep, school, work, and mood, and about coexisting asthma, which you should always check and optimise. Examine the nose for pale, swollen, boggy mucosa and exclude polyps and structural problems. Allergy testing — skin-prick or specific IgE — is occasionally needed to identify triggers, particularly before immunotherapy. Management: begin with the non-drug foundation — allergen avoidance where feasible, recognising it is only ever partly achievable; for house dust mite, measures such as mattress covers and reducing soft furnishings; for pollen, simple steps like keeping windows shut at peak times, wraparound sunglasses, and showering after being outdoors; and a saline nasal rinse, which is cheap, safe and genuinely helpful. For mild or intermittent symptoms, offer an as-needed oral or intranasal antihistamine. For moderate-to-severe or persistent symptoms, the most effective treatment is a regular intranasal corticosteroid, started ahead of the season and used with correct technique — and getting the technique right is the commonest reason for treatment seeming to fail, so demonstrate it. A non-sedating antihistamine can be added for breakthrough symptoms, and treat eye symptoms with antihistamine or mast-cell-stabiliser drops. Reserve intranasal decongestants for very short-term use only, warning that prolonged use causes rebound congestion. Now safety-netting and review: tell the patient that the steroid spray takes days to weeks to work fully and must be used regularly rather than only when bad, and to return if symptoms remain uncontrolled despite correct, consistent treatment, or if asthma control worsens. Refer for diagnostic uncertainty, symptoms uncontrolled despite optimal treatment, suspected occupational rhinitis, nasal polyps, or for consideration of immunotherapy. Reassess control and inhaler and spray technique at follow-up, and always remember to optimise any coexisting asthma.' },

  { id:'cks-cough', cat:'Respiratory', ic:'😷', dur:'5 min', title:'Cough', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for cough in adults. In plain language for the patient: a cough is the body\u2019s way of clearing the airways, and most coughs come from a simple viral infection and settle on their own within a couple of weeks, even if they linger a little longer. The job of the assessment is mainly to make sure there is nothing more serious behind it and to treat any specific cause. Cough is classified by duration: acute under three weeks, subacute three to eight weeks, and chronic over eight weeks. Red flags first, because they are the priority: under NICE NG12, offer an urgent chest X-ray within two weeks for anyone aged 40 and over with unexplained haemoptysis, and consider one for a persistent or changing cough, especially in current or former smokers. Other alarm features needing prompt assessment include weight loss, significant breathlessness, chest pain, fever with focal chest signs suggesting pneumonia, a hoarse voice persisting beyond three weeks, or difficulty swallowing. Now the risk factors and common causes: smoking is central; acute cough is usually post-viral; and chronic cough commonly comes from asthma, gastro-oesophageal reflux, upper airway cough syndrome from post-nasal drip, ACE inhibitor use, COPD, and smoking itself. Assessment: ask about the duration, sputum, haemoptysis, breathlessness, fever, weight loss, heartburn, nasal symptoms, occupational exposures, medications, and smoking. Examine the chest and the observations. Investigate chronic cough with a chest X-ray and spirometry, and tailor further tests to the suspected cause. Management: for acute viral cough, the most useful intervention is clear explanation and reassurance — advise rest, fluids, and honey, which has evidence for symptom relief, and explain that antibiotics do not help a viral cough and that the cough may take up to three or four weeks to fully settle. Stop a causative ACE inhibitor and review, switching to an ARB. Treat the identified underlying cause of chronic cough — a trial of asthma treatment, reflux measures such as weight loss, smaller meals and not eating late, or a nasal corticosteroid for upper airway cough syndrome. Now the non-drug and lifestyle measures: smoking cessation is the most important and often resolves a smoker\u2019s cough; reduce reflux triggers; and avoid occupational or environmental irritants. Now safety-netting, which is the heart of managing acute cough safely: tell the patient to seek review if the cough lasts more than three weeks, if they cough up blood, lose weight, become breathless, develop chest pain or a high fever, or simply are not improving as expected. Refer urgently per NG12 for suspected lung cancer, and refer to respiratory services for a chronic cough of unclear cause despite initial management, an abnormal chest X-ray, or suspected serious pathology. Always reinforce smoking cessation, and reassess any cough that persists, changes in character, or develops alarm features.' },

  { id:'cks-bronchiectasis', cat:'Respiratory', ic:'🫁', dur:'5 min', title:'Bronchiectasis', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for bronchiectasis. In plain language for the patient: bronchiectasis means some of the airways in the lungs have become permanently widened and scarred, so mucus collects there instead of clearing, which leads to a persistent phlegmy cough and repeated chest infections. It is a long-term condition, but with daily airway-clearance exercises and prompt treatment of infections most people keep it well controlled and stay active. Definition: permanent abnormal dilatation of the bronchi with chronic inflammation and impaired mucociliary clearance. Red flags first: a significant or massive haemoptysis is an emergency; worsening breathlessness with fever and feeling very unwell may indicate severe infection or sepsis; and progressive weight loss or a change in symptoms should prompt thinking about other pathology, including malignancy and tuberculosis or other mycobacterial infection. Now the risk factors and causes: previous severe infection such as pneumonia, whooping cough or tuberculosis; immunodeficiency; cystic fibrosis; allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis; connective tissue disease such as rheumatoid arthritis; and aspiration — though many cases are idiopathic. Assessment: suspect bronchiectasis in a person with a chronic productive cough, large volumes of sputum, recurrent chest infections, and breathlessness, sometimes with haemoptysis. Examine for coarse crackles and clubbing. The diagnosis is confirmed on high-resolution CT of the chest, arranged via specialists. Send sputum for culture, including for atypical mycobacteria, and investigate the underlying cause with bloods including immunoglobulins. Management is shared with respiratory specialists, and the cornerstone is non-drug: airway clearance. Teach and strongly encourage daily chest physiotherapy techniques and refer to respiratory physiotherapy — this is the single most important day-to-day treatment, and consistency matters. Encourage regular exercise and pulmonary rehabilitation, ensure vaccinations, optimise nutrition, and treat any coexisting condition such as asthma or reflux. Treat exacerbations — marked by increased sputum volume, increased purulence, or worsening breathlessness — promptly with a prolonged antibiotic course, typically fourteen days, guided where possible by previous sputum culture results. For frequent exacerbations, specialists may consider long-term prophylactic antibiotics such as azithromycin, with the necessary cardiac and liver monitoring and checks for mycobacterial infection first. Now safety-netting: give patients a clear self-management plan, teach them to recognise an exacerbation early and when to start antibiotics or seek help, and tell them to seek urgent attention for coughing up significant blood, high fever, or rapidly worsening breathlessness. Refer to respiratory services for diagnosis and ongoing specialist input, particularly for frequent exacerbations, declining lung function, haemoptysis, or isolation of resistant or mycobacterial organisms. Review regularly for symptom control, exacerbation frequency, sputum microbiology, and lung function, and ensure airway clearance and rescue arrangements are in place.' },

  { id:'cks-smoking', cat:'Respiratory', ic:'🚭', dur:'5 min', title:'Smoking cessation', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for smoking cessation. In plain language for the patient: smoking is the single biggest preventable cause of illness and early death, but the body begins to recover remarkably quickly after stopping — within a year the excess risk of heart disease roughly halves, and over time the risks fall close to those of a non-smoker. Stopping is hard because nicotine is genuinely addictive, but the right combination of support and medication makes success several times more likely, and most people who quit have made more than one attempt — so a previous relapse is not failure, it is part of the process. Supporting cessation is one of the most effective interventions in all of medicine. There are no red flags as such, but recognise that stopping abruptly can alter the dose requirements of some drugs — notably theophylline, clozapine and olanzapine, whose levels rise when smoking stops — and that this needs monitoring. Now the assessment: ask all patients about smoking status and record it, and at every opportunity offer very brief advice — ask about smoking, advise that the most effective way to stop is with support and medication, and act by offering a referral. Assess nicotine dependence from how soon after waking the person smokes and how much, and explore previous attempts, what helped, and what triggered relapse, as well as their motivation and confidence. Management: the most effective approach combines behavioural support with pharmacotherapy, which together substantially increase quit rates compared with willpower alone. Refer to local stop-smoking services for structured behavioural support, which is itself one of the strongest predictors of success. Offer pharmacotherapy: nicotine replacement therapy, ideally combining a long-acting patch with a fast-acting form such as gum, lozenge, inhalator or spray for breakthrough cravings; varenicline where available; or bupropion. Nicotine-containing e-cigarettes are an effective aid that many find helpful, and can be recommended as a substantially less harmful alternative to smoking for those who want to use them. Now the non-drug behavioural techniques worth coaching: set a definite quit date and stop completely on that day; identify and plan for trigger situations; remove cigarettes, lighters and ashtrays; use the support service; and manage cravings, which are intense but pass within minutes, with distraction, activity, and the fast-acting nicotine product. Now safety-netting and follow-up: warn that cravings, irritability and disturbed sleep are temporary withdrawal effects, not signs that quitting is not working; arrange follow-up to support and to manage any lapse without judgement, treating it as a learning point rather than a failure; and re-engage people who relapse, since each attempt raises the odds of eventual success. Tailor advice in pregnancy, where behavioural support is first-line and nicotine replacement may be used after discussion, and in mental illness, where stopping is achievable and beneficial with the right support. Reinforce cessation at every contact, and celebrate the rapid and lifelong health gains of stopping at any age.' },

  /* ---------------- ENDOCRINE ---------------- */
  { id:'cks-t2dm', cat:'Endocrine', ic:'🩸', dur:'5 min', title:'Type 2 diabetes', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for type 2 diabetes, following NICE guideline NG28. In plain language for the patient: in type 2 diabetes the body either does not make enough insulin or cannot use it properly, so the sugar level in the blood runs too high. Over years, that high sugar quietly damages blood vessels and nerves, which is why it raises the risk of heart attacks, strokes, kidney, eye, nerve and foot problems. The encouraging part is that it responds powerfully to changes in diet, weight and activity — to the point that significant weight loss can even push it into remission in some people — alongside well-established medicines. Definition: a chronic metabolic disorder of insulin resistance and relative insulin deficiency causing hyperglycaemia. Red flags first: features of very high glucose with ketones, vomiting, abdominal pain, and breathlessness suggest diabetic ketoacidosis or a hyperosmolar state — medical emergencies, and a reminder to reconsider type 1 diabetes or pancreatic disease in someone who is markedly unwell, thin, or ketotic. The diabetic foot with infection, ulceration or sudden colour change is an urgent, limb-threatening problem. Now the risk factors: increasing age, overweight and central obesity, physical inactivity, a family history, certain ethnic backgrounds including South Asian, African and Caribbean, previous gestational diabetes, and conditions such as polycystic ovary syndrome. Assessment and diagnosis: diagnose in an asymptomatic person with two abnormal results, or one result with symptoms — an HbA1c of 48 millimoles per mole or more, or a fasting glucose of 7 or more — being aware that HbA1c is unreliable in pregnancy, recent acute illness, and some anaemias. At diagnosis, assess for complications and cardiovascular risk: check renal function and the urine albumin-to-creatinine ratio, lipids, blood pressure, arrange retinal screening, and examine the feet. Management: reinforce structured education and the non-drug foundation throughout, and I would put this first — dietary change toward a healthier pattern, weight loss where appropriate, increased activity, reducing alcohol, and stopping smoking, with an explicit conversation about the possibility of remission through substantial, sustained weight loss. Start metformin and titrate slowly, using the modified-release form if it upsets the stomach. At the same time, assess cardiovascular status: if there is established cardiovascular disease, heart failure, or high risk, add an SGLT2 inhibitor with proven benefit regardless of the HbA1c. For further glucose control, intensify with a DPP-4 inhibitor, a sulfonylurea, pioglitazone, or an SGLT2 inhibitor, then consider a GLP-1 receptor agonist where obesity is prominent and criteria are met. Individualise the HbA1c target — 48 on lifestyle or drugs not causing hypoglycaemia, or 53 on a sulfonylurea or insulin — and relax targets in frailty. Manage cardiovascular risk actively with a statin and blood-pressure control, offer an ACE inhibitor or ARB for albuminuria, and use SGLT2 inhibitors for renal and cardiac protection. Now safety-netting and self-care: teach those on sulfonylureas or insulin to recognise and treat hypoglycaemia, advise sick-day rules, give clear foot-care advice and when to seek same-day help for a foot problem, and ensure attendance at annual retinal screening and foot and renal checks. Refer for poor control despite escalation, suspected type 1 or other diabetes, pregnancy or planning, and complications such as a diabetic foot, significant retinopathy, or progressive kidney disease. Review at least annually, revisiting the message that what the patient does day to day with food, weight and activity is as powerful as any tablet.' },

  { id:'cks-t1dm', cat:'Endocrine', ic:'💉', dur:'5 min', title:'Type 1 diabetes', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for type 1 diabetes in adults. In plain language for the patient: type 1 diabetes happens when the immune system destroys the cells in the pancreas that make insulin, so the body can no longer produce it at all. Insulin is the hormone that lets sugar move from the blood into the body\u2019s cells for energy, so without it the blood sugar climbs dangerously high. It is not caused by lifestyle and could not have been prevented. It is managed with lifelong insulin, and with modern insulins, glucose monitors and education, people live full and active lives — the skill is in balancing insulin, food and activity. Definition: autoimmune destruction of pancreatic beta cells causing absolute insulin deficiency. Red flags first, and this is the crucial one: diabetic ketoacidosis — high glucose with ketones, vomiting, abdominal pain, deep or laboured breathing, and drowsiness — is a life-threatening emergency needing immediate admission. Suspect type 1 rather than type 2 in someone presenting with hyperglycaemia who has ketosis, rapid onset, marked weight loss, a younger age, or a low BMI, though it can present at any age — and do not delay treatment while waiting for tests if they are unwell. Now the risk factors: a personal or family history of autoimmune disease, such as thyroid disease or coeliac disease, and genetic predisposition, though most have no family history. Assessment: confirm and initiate care with specialist diabetes services. Check for the autoimmune associations and assess for complications once established. Management is specialist-led but with an important primary-care role. Insulin is essential and lifelong, usually as a basal-bolus regimen or an insulin pump, with carbohydrate counting and structured education such as the DAFNE programme. Support self-monitoring of glucose, increasingly with continuous or flash glucose monitors, aiming for individualised targets — typically an HbA1c of 48 or below where achievable without problematic hypoglycaemia. Now the non-drug and self-management essentials, which are the heart of living with type 1: education in matching insulin to carbohydrate and activity; recognising and treating hypoglycaemia; and sick-day rules, which are vital — never stop insulin during illness, check glucose and ketones more often, and maintain carbohydrate and fluids, seeking help if ketones rise or vomiting prevents fluids. Screen for and manage complications — annual retinal screening, foot checks, renal function and ACR — and address cardiovascular risk. Support psychological wellbeing, as the relentless self-management is demanding, and offer the necessary vaccinations. Now safety-netting: ensure every patient knows the warning signs of ketoacidosis and to seek urgent help; that they can recognise and treat a hypo and that severe or recurrent hypos, or loss of hypo awareness, need review; and how to manage illness safely. The primary-care role is recognising new presentations and referring promptly, supporting between specialist reviews, managing intercurrent illness, coordinating complication screening, and being alert to associated autoimmune conditions. Refer or admit for ketoacidosis, recurrent severe or unaware hypoglycaemia, pregnancy planning, and persistently poor control.' },

  { id:'cks-hypothyroid', cat:'Endocrine', ic:'🦋', dur:'5 min', title:'Hypothyroidism', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for hypothyroidism, following NICE guideline NG145. In plain language for the patient: the thyroid is a small gland in the neck that sets the body\u2019s pace, like a thermostat. When it is underactive it makes too little thyroid hormone, so everything slows down — you feel tired, cold, low, constipated, and may gain weight. It is common, easily diagnosed with a blood test, and treated simply and effectively by replacing the missing hormone with a daily tablet, which most people take for life. Definition: underactivity of the thyroid causing reduced thyroid hormone, most commonly from autoimmune thyroiditis or as a consequence of thyroid treatment. Red flags first: myxoedema coma — hypothermia, marked drowsiness or reduced consciousness in a severely hypothyroid, often elderly, patient — is a rare emergency. In pregnancy and when planning it, under-treatment carries real risk to the developing baby and needs prompt specialist-guided adjustment. New thyroid replacement in someone with known heart disease can precipitate angina, so start low. Now the risk factors: female sex, increasing age, a personal or family history of autoimmune disease, previous thyroid surgery or radioactive iodine, neck radiotherapy, and certain drugs such as amiodarone and lithium. Assessment: symptoms are often non-specific — fatigue, weight gain, cold intolerance, constipation, dry skin, low mood, menstrual changes, and slowed thinking. Diagnose biochemically: overt primary hypothyroidism is a raised TSH with a low free T4; subclinical hypothyroidism is a raised TSH with a normal free T4. Check thyroid peroxidase antibodies where autoimmune disease is suspected, and avoid testing during acute illness, which causes misleading sick-euthyroid changes. Management: for overt primary hypothyroidism, start levothyroxine. In young, otherwise healthy adults, start at a full replacement dose of around 1.6 micrograms per kilogram daily; in those over 65 or with cardiac disease, start low, at 25 to 50 micrograms, and titrate gently to avoid precipitating cardiac problems. Recheck TSH and adjust every six to eight weeks until stable, then check annually, aiming for a TSH within the reference range, typically 0.5 to 2.5 in younger adults, guided by symptoms. Now the non-drug and practical advice that makes treatment work: take levothyroxine on an empty stomach, ideally 30 to 60 minutes before breakfast, and separate it from calcium, iron, and coffee, which block absorption; take it consistently and at the same time; and explain that it can take weeks for symptoms to improve after the dose is right, and that the dose may need adjusting over time. For subclinical hypothyroidism, consider a levothyroxine trial if the TSH is above 10, or if it is between the upper limit and 10 with symptoms or positive antibodies, particularly in those under 65. Now safety-netting: advise patients to report symptoms of over-treatment — palpitations, tremor, heat intolerance, weight loss — since too much carries risks of atrial fibrillation and osteoporosis, and to seek advice promptly if they become pregnant. Refer for pregnancy or planning, suspected secondary hypothyroidism, cardiac disease complicating treatment, or diagnostic uncertainty. Review adherence and symptoms, avoid over-replacement, and reassure that, once settled, this is a very manageable lifelong condition.' },

  { id:'cks-hyperthyroid', cat:'Endocrine', ic:'🦋', dur:'5 min', title:'Hyperthyroidism', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for hyperthyroidism. In plain language for the patient: here the thyroid gland in the neck is overactive and makes too much thyroid hormone, so the body speeds up — you may feel your heart racing, lose weight despite a good appetite, feel hot, sweaty, anxious, shaky and have looser bowels. It is very treatable; the approach is to calm the symptoms quickly and then bring the gland under control with medication, or sometimes radioiodine or surgery. Definition: excess thyroid hormone, most commonly from Graves\u2019 disease, a toxic multinodular goitre, or a toxic adenoma. Red flags first: thyroid storm — severe thyrotoxicosis with high fever, a very fast or irregular heart rhythm, agitation and confusion — is a life-threatening emergency. New atrial fibrillation, especially in older patients, and Graves\u2019 eye disease with pain or visual loss, both need urgent attention. And a crucial drug-safety red flag to teach: anyone started on an antithyroid drug such as carbimazole must know that a sore throat, mouth ulcers, fever or flu-like illness could mean a dangerous drop in white cells, agranulocytosis, and they must stop the drug and have an urgent full blood count. Now the risk factors: female sex, a family or personal history of autoimmune disease, and excess iodine, including from amiodarone. Assessment: suspect it from weight loss, heat intolerance, palpitations, tremor, anxiety, sweating, diarrhoea, and menstrual change. Examine for tachycardia or atrial fibrillation, a fine tremor, a goitre, and, in Graves\u2019 disease, eye signs such as exophthalmos and lid retraction. Diagnose biochemically: overt hyperthyroidism is a suppressed TSH with a raised free T4 or T3; subclinical hyperthyroidism is a suppressed TSH with normal hormone levels. Check TSH-receptor antibodies for Graves\u2019 disease, and specialists may arrange isotope scanning to determine the cause. Management: refer to endocrinology for confirmation and definitive treatment — antithyroid drugs such as carbimazole, radioactive iodine, or surgery. In primary care, while awaiting specialist review, a beta-blocker such as propranolol gives rapid symptomatic relief of the adrenergic symptoms, unless contraindicated. Now the non-drug and supportive measures: reassure and explain the plan; advise reducing caffeine and stimulants, which worsen palpitations and tremor; offer smoking-cessation support, as smoking worsens thyroid eye disease; and manage atrial fibrillation including thromboembolic risk. Now safety-netting: make the agranulocytosis warning explicit and in writing; advise seeking urgent help for severe symptoms, fever, or chest symptoms; and counsel anyone who might become pregnant to seek prompt advice, as treatment differs in pregnancy with propylthiouracil generally preferred in the first trimester under specialist care. Refer urgently for thyroid eye disease with visual symptoms, suspected thyroid storm, and in pregnancy. Review symptoms and thyroid function during and after treatment, and watch for subsequent hypothyroidism after definitive therapy, which is common and itself needs treatment.' },

  { id:'cks-obesity', cat:'Endocrine', ic:'⚖️', dur:'5 min', title:'Obesity', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for obesity in adults. In plain language for the patient: obesity means carrying enough extra body fat to harm health, and it is not simply a matter of willpower — it is driven by biology, environment, medication, sleep, stress and circumstances as much as by choice. It matters because it raises the risk of type 2 diabetes, heart disease, several cancers, joint problems, sleep apnoea and low mood. The hopeful message is that even a modest, sustained weight loss of five to ten percent produces real health benefits, and there is now genuinely effective support, including newer medicines and surgery for those who need them. Definition: excess body fat that impairs health, classified by BMI — overweight 25 to 29.9, obesity class 1 from 30, class 2 from 35, class 3 from 40 — with lower thresholds for people of South Asian and some other ethnic backgrounds, interpreted alongside waist measurement. Red flags and things not to miss: consider an underlying medical cause where the story fits — hypothyroidism, Cushing\u2019s syndrome, or weight gain from drugs such as steroids, some antipsychotics and antidepressants; screen for the serious comorbidities, especially type 2 diabetes and obstructive sleep apnoea; and be alert to disordered eating and to the mental-health impact, including the harm of weight stigma. Now the risk factors and contributors: genetic predisposition, an obesogenic food environment, physical inactivity, poor sleep, stress, lower income, certain medications, and life stages such as pregnancy and the menopause. Assessment: measure BMI and waist circumference, which adds information particularly at lower BMI. Assess for causes and contributors, screen for comorbidities — check HbA1c, blood pressure, lipids, and ask about snoring and daytime sleepiness — and explore eating patterns, psychological factors, and the person\u2019s own goals and readiness. Raise the subject sensitively and with permission. Management: take a respectful, non-stigmatising, collaborative approach. The foundation is a multicomponent lifestyle intervention — a sustainable reduced-calorie, balanced diet, increased physical activity, and behavioural support — ideally through a structured weight-management programme, and I would frame this around achievable, lasting habit change rather than short-term dieting. Set realistic goals such as a 5 to 10 percent loss. Consider pharmacotherapy as an adjunct for those meeting criteria — orlistat, or GLP-1-based therapies through the appropriate pathways and specialist services. Refer to specialist or tier-3 weight-management services for complex cases, and consider bariatric surgery for those with class 3 obesity, or class 2 with a significant comorbidity such as type 2 diabetes, who meet the criteria, as it is highly effective and can resolve diabetes. Now safety-netting and review: treat the comorbidities actively, support the maintenance phase to prevent regain — which is the hardest part — and revisit weight constructively at relevant contacts. Refer for suspected secondary causes, eating disorders, or when specialist or surgical options are appropriate, and reinforce throughout that small, sustained changes compound into meaningful health gains.' },

  { id:'cks-addisons', cat:'Endocrine', ic:'🧂', dur:'5 min', title:'Addison\u2019s disease', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for Addison\u2019s disease, primary adrenal insufficiency. In plain language for the patient: the adrenal glands, which sit on top of the kidneys, make cortisol — a hormone essential for handling stress and illness — and usually a salt-balancing hormone too. In Addison\u2019s disease these glands fail, so the body cannot produce enough. The symptoms creep up slowly — tiredness, weight loss, dizziness, and sometimes a tan-like darkening of the skin. The vital thing to understand is that the missing hormones are replaced with tablets, and that during any illness the body needs more, so knowing the sick-day rules and carrying emergency treatment is genuinely life-saving. Definition: inadequate production of cortisol and usually aldosterone from adrenal cortex destruction, most often autoimmune in the UK. Red flags first, and this dominates management: an Addisonian crisis — hypotension, vomiting, collapse, abdominal pain, and shock, often triggered by illness, injury or surgery — is a life-threatening emergency requiring immediate intramuscular or intravenous hydrocortisone and admission, without waiting for any test results. Now the risk factors: other autoimmune conditions such as type 1 diabetes, thyroid disease and pernicious anaemia, and a family history of autoimmune disease; worldwide, tuberculosis is an important cause. Assessment: the presentation is often insidious and non-specific — fatigue, weakness, weight loss, anorexia, nausea, abdominal pain, dizziness from postural hypotension, and salt craving — so a high index of suspicion is needed. Look for hyperpigmentation, especially of skin creases, scars and the inside of the mouth, and for postural hypotension. Biochemical clues include low sodium, raised potassium, and sometimes low glucose. Confirm with a short Synacthen test showing an inadequate cortisol response; a low 9am cortisol is suggestive, and adrenal autoantibodies support an autoimmune cause. Management is specialist-led with lifelong glucocorticoid replacement, usually hydrocortisone in divided doses, and the mineralocorticoid fludrocortisone. The vital primary-care role is education and crisis prevention, which I want to emphasise as the core non-drug intervention: every patient needs the sick-day rules — double the glucocorticoid dose during fever or significant illness, and use emergency intramuscular hydrocortisone for vomiting or severe illness — a steroid emergency card, a medical-alert bracelet or necklace, and the clear instruction never to stop steroids abruptly. Ensure they have injectable hydrocortisone at home and that they and a family member know how to use it. Now safety-netting: make sure the patient and their family can recognise an impending crisis, know to give emergency hydrocortisone and call 999, and understand that vomiting means they cannot absorb tablets and need the injection. Refer urgently for suspected new disease, and admit immediately for a crisis. Review adherence, sick-day knowledge, blood pressure and electrolytes, and coordinate closely with endocrinology, especially around illness, surgery, dental procedures, and pregnancy.' },

  { id:'cks-b12', cat:'Endocrine', ic:'🧪', dur:'5 min', title:'B12 & folate deficiency', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for vitamin B12 and folate deficiency. In plain language for the patient: vitamin B12 and folate are needed to make healthy red blood cells, and B12 is also needed to keep the nerves working. When either runs low, the blood cells become large and few, causing anaemia with tiredness and breathlessness; and a lack of B12 can, if untreated, damage the nerves, causing numbness, tingling and balance problems. Both are easily measured and treated — often with injections for B12 and tablets for folate — and treating B12 promptly protects the nerves. Definition: deficiency of these vitamins impairs red-cell production, causing a macrocytic anaemia, and B12 deficiency can additionally cause neurological damage. Red flags first: neurological features of B12 deficiency — numbness, pins and needles, unsteadiness, or cognitive change — need prompt treatment to prevent permanent damage; severe anaemia with cardiac symptoms needs urgent assessment; and a key safety principle — if both B12 and folate are low, always replace B12 first, because giving folate alone can precipitate or worsen subacute combined degeneration of the spinal cord. Now the risk factors and causes: for B12, pernicious anaemia — an autoimmune condition reducing intrinsic factor — malabsorption, gastric or ileal surgery, certain drugs such as metformin and long-term proton-pump inhibitors, and a strict vegan diet; for folate, a poor diet, malabsorption such as coeliac disease, increased demand in pregnancy, and drugs such as methotrexate. Assessment: ask about fatigue, breathlessness, glossitis, and, for B12, the neurological symptoms; examine for pallor and for a peripheral neuropathy or signs of cord involvement. Investigate with a full blood count and film showing macrocytosis, and serum B12 and folate; check intrinsic factor antibodies where pernicious anaemia is suspected, and consider coeliac serology. Management: for B12 deficiency, give intramuscular hydroxocobalamin — a loading regimen then maintenance injections, with more intensive loading if there are neurological features; pernicious anaemia needs lifelong injections, while dietary deficiency may respond to oral B12. For folate deficiency, give oral folic acid, having first excluded or treated coexisting B12 deficiency, and address dietary causes. Now the non-drug and lifestyle advice: for dietary causes, counsel on B12 sources — meat, fish, eggs, dairy, and fortified foods for vegans, who should take a supplement — and folate sources such as green vegetables, pulses and fortified cereals; and remember folic acid supplementation before and in early pregnancy to prevent neural tube defects. Now safety-netting: advise patients to report new or worsening neurological symptoms promptly, and explain that the anaemia improves over weeks once treatment starts, with a blood count check to confirm response. Refer for neurological involvement needing urgent treatment, suspected malignancy, severe anaemia, diagnostic uncertainty, or suspected malabsorption. Review symptoms and counts, arrange appropriate long-term monitoring, and remember the small increased risk of gastric cancer in pernicious anaemia.' },

  { id:'cks-vitd', cat:'Endocrine', ic:'☀️', dur:'5 min', title:'Vitamin D deficiency', sub:'CKS clinician summary',
    body:'This is the clinical summary for vitamin D deficiency in adults. In plain language for the patient: vitamin D helps the body absorb calcium and keep bones and muscles strong, and we make most of it in the skin from summer sunlight, topping up from a few foods. In the UK, low levels are common, especially in winter, and a serious lack can cause bone pain and muscle weakness — and in severe cases soft bones, called osteomalacia. It is straightforward to put right with supplements, and for many people a simple daily supplement in the darker months is sensible prevention. Definition: low vitamin D, needed for calcium and bone metabolism; severe prolonged deficiency causes osteomalacia in adults and rickets in children, and it contributes to osteoporosis. Red flags and things not to miss: significant bone pain with muscle weakness may indicate osteomalacia; and importantly, do not give high-dose vitamin D before checking calcium if primary hyperparathyroidism is possible, and investigate unexplained high calcium. Now the risk factors: limited sun exposure, darker skin, covering the skin, older age and housebound status, obesity, malabsorption such as coeliac or inflammatory bowel disease, and some medications. Assessment: vitamin D is not recommended as a routine screening test in people without symptoms. Test the serum 25-hydroxyvitamin D where there are symptoms suggesting deficiency — bone pain, proximal muscle weakness, or suspected osteomalacia — or in high-risk individuals where the result will change management. Interpret the level: below 25 nanomoles per litre indicates deficiency, 25 to 50 may be inadequate, and above 50 is generally sufficient. Check calcium, phosphate, alkaline phosphatase and renal function, and consider an underlying cause if deficiency is unexplained or recurrent. Management: for confirmed deficiency, give a loading regimen of colecalciferol — for example a total of around 300,000 units split over six to ten weeks — followed by regular maintenance supplementation. For people at risk, or for maintenance, recommend a daily supplement, commonly 400 to 800 units, in line with public-health advice that everyone consider a supplement in autumn and winter and that at-risk groups supplement year-round. Now the non-drug and lifestyle advice: encourage safe sun exposure in summer without burning, and dietary sources such as oily fish, eggs, and fortified foods; and correct any coexisting low calcium. Now safety-netting and review: recheck calcium if high-dose treatment is given, particularly where hyperparathyroidism is possible; advise that bone and muscle symptoms improve over weeks to months; and ensure ongoing maintenance, since levels fall again if supplementation stops in someone with persisting risk. Refer for an unclear cause, malabsorption, abnormal calcium or renal function, or suspected osteomalacia or metabolic bone disease, and treat any associated osteoporosis on its own pathway.' },

];
